    <div class="about-content">
      <h1 class="about-title">About The Wooden Spoon</h1>

      <div class="about-intro">
        <p class="about-lead">Hi, I'm Sarah. I cook things and write about them.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="about-body">
        <p>I started The Wooden Spoon because I was tired of recipe blogs that require you to scroll through someone's entire life story before you get to the part where they tell you how much garlic to use. (It's always more garlic than they say, by the way.)</p>

        <p>That said, I do believe food is personal. Every recipe here comes with a short story &mdash; not because you need my emotional backstory to make fried rice, but because context makes food more interesting. Where a recipe came from, why it works, what I learned from getting it wrong twenty times before I got it right.</p>

        <h2>What you'll find here</h2>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Tested recipes.</strong> Every recipe on this site has been made at least a dozen times. If it doesn't work reliably, it doesn't make the cut.</li>
          <li><strong>Honest difficulty ratings.</strong> If something is hard, I'll tell you it's hard. If it's easy, I won't pad it with unnecessary steps to make it look impressive.</li>
          <li><strong>Real ingredients.</strong> No truffle oil (okay, a little truffle oil on the risotto), no high-end ingredients you can't find at a regular grocery store.</li>
          <li><strong>Proper JSON-LD structured data.</strong> Because I'm also a nerd, and I believe recipe data should be machine-readable.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A note on the recipes</h2>

        <p>I cook the way most home cooks cook: imprecisely, improvisationally, and with whatever's in the fridge. The recipes here are my best attempt to translate that into something reproducible. Cooking times are approximate. "Season to taste" means I trust you to know what tastes good to you.</p>

        <p>If something doesn't work, it's probably my fault and I'd love to hear about it. If something does work and you make it your own, that's the whole point.</p>

        <h2>About the name</h2>

        <p>Every kitchen I've ever cooked in has had a wooden spoon. Not a fancy one &mdash; a beat-up, stained, slightly warped wooden spoon that's been used to stir a thousand pots. It's the most honest tool in the kitchen. No pretension, no technology, just wood and heat and time.</p>

        <p>That's what I want this blog to be.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

